President Donald J. Trump has declared a state of emergency in Georgia due to the emergency conditions caused by Hurricane Michael. This declaration authorizes the Department of Homeland Security and the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) to coordinate disaster relief efforts. FEMA is authorized to provide equipment and resources to alleviate the impacts of the emergency. Debris removal and emergency protective measures will be provided at 75 percent federal funding in certain counties, while emergency protective measures will be provided at 75 percent funding in other counties. Manny J. Toro has been named the Federal Coordinating Officer for federal recovery operations in the affected areas. For further information, the media can contact the FEMA news desk.